            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                
                <p>I have taken the earliest opportunity of forwarding a trifling acknowledgement of the favors you have done me, and hope you will 
                    <sic>recieve</sic> it safe.    
                </p>
                <p>By Yesterdays Post I was dunned for my long promise of sea weeds to her <persName ref="pe0148">grace of Chandos</persName>: 
                    you will be the means of saving my credit for ever, by returning me the Box (I have sent) full of such plants as your Rocks 
                    afford.<note type="editorial">The tentative suggestion that this unaddressed letter was intended for William Morris is made on the evidence
                    provided in this sentence, set alongside a letter of 11 November 1754 from William to his brother Richard. William mentions the receipt of a
                    letter and a box containing twenty six parcels of curiositis ('fossil shells, plant, animals, mines, minerals, etc') from Pennant on his return from an absence from home
                    and the request that he should quickly fill the box with the 'wonders of Anglesey' ('r[h]yfeddodau MÃ´n'). See 
                    <hi rend="italic">ML</hi>, I, p. 318.</note> Be so kind as to direct it to me to the care of <persName ref="pe0149">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sidebotham</persName> 
                    at the <placeName ref="pl3323">antelope</placeName> <placeName ref="pl1251">Holywell</placeName>, and that as soon as possible which 
                    will much oblige
                </p>
                <closer><salute>Dear Sir
                    <lb/>Yours most truly</salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant
                    </persName></signed>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1754
                    </dateline></closer>
                <postscript><p/></postscript>
            </div>
